value.value: A dendritic cell that develops from a monocyte.

An enterocyte that possesses a large supranuclear vacuolar system that preferentially internalizes dietary protein via receptor-mediated and fluid-phase endocytosis for intracellular digestion and trans-cellular transport. In zebrafish these cells are located in the posterior region of the mid intestine throughout life. In mammals they are found in the ileum pre-weaning and later are replaced by mature enterocytes.
Neuron that secretes the neurotransmitter galanin.

Cells of the uterine chorion that acquire specialized structural and/or functional features that characterize chorionic trophoblasts. These cells will migrate towards the spongiotrophoblast layer and give rise to syncytiotrophoblasts of the labyrinthine layer.
Parasympathetic neurons are part of the parasympathetic nervous sysem and the cell bodies lie in the brain and sacral region of the spinal cord. The neurons are mainly cholinergic.
Sympathetic neurons are part of the sympathetic nervous system and are primarily adrenergic producing the neurotransmitter noradrenalin along with other neuropeptides.

A type of interneuron in the retinal inner nuclear layer which
carries information from the inner plexiform layer and the outer
plexiform layer.

definition.value: Need to MIREOT retinal inner nuclear layer (part of)

value.value:
A type of interneuron in the retinal inner nuclear layer which
carries information from the inner plexiform layer and the outer
plexiform layer, using dopamine.

definition.value: This type of cell is found in Danio rerio.

value.value:
A type of interneuron in the retinal inner nuclear layer which
carries information from the inner plexiform layer and the outer
plexiform layer using GABA.

definition.value: This type of cell is found in many mammals.

value.value: Epithelial cell that is part of the colon epithelium.
A neuron that releases hypocretin as a neurotransmitter.
Neuron that secretes histamine.

A neuroendocrine cell that secretes gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH). A GnRH neuron is born in the nasal placode during embryonic development and migrates through the nose and forebrain to the hypothalamus. This cell regulates reproduction by secreting GnRH into the pituitary portal vessels to induce the release of gonadotropins into the general circulation.
Neuron found in the spiral ganglion.

A segmented neutrophilic cell of the bone marrow reserve pool that expresses CD11b (integrin alpha-M) and high levels of CD16 (low affinity immunoglobulin gamma Fc region receptor III) on its cell surface.
A cell that, by division or terminal differentiation, can give rise to other cell types.

definition.value: Work is needed on GO 'cell differentiation' before it is clear whether the equivalent class definition 'native cell' that capable_of some 'cell differentiation' works. Also, may want to consider merging this with non-terminally differentiated cell.
A CNS neuron of the forebrain.

value.value: Motor neuron that innervate muscles that control eye, jaw, and facial movements of the vertebrate head and parasympathetic neurons that innervate certain glands and organs.
An ionocyte that is part of the lung epithelium. The cells from this type are major sources of the CFTR protein in human and mice.

definition.value: A mesodermal cell that is part of the splanchnic layer of lateral plate mesoderm.

value.value: A neuroendocrine cell that is part of the prostate epithelium.
An epithelial cell that is part of the prostatic urethra.
A lymphocyte of B lineage that has gotten larger after being stimulated by an antigen.
A human dendritic cell that expresses the AXL and SIGLEC6 genes.
A hillock cell that is part of the urethra.

label.value: hillock cell of prostatic urethral epithelium

value.value: A hillock cell that is part of the prostatic urethra.
Cytoplasm that exhibits a characteristic staining and color, pale-pink, with Wright-Giemsa stain.
Cytoplasm that exhibits a characteristic staining and color, red or pink, with Eosin stain.
Cytoplasm that exhibits molecular interaction for basic dyes under specific pH conditions.
Cytoplasm that exhibits affinity for both basic and acid stains under specific pH conditions.
A nucleus size quality which is relatively high compared to the amount of cytoplasm present in the same cell.
A concave nuclear shape where the nucleus is indented to more than half the distance to the farthest nuclear margin, but in no area is the chromatin condensed to a single filament.
A concave nucleus shape where the indentation is smaller than half of the distance to the farthest nuclear margin.
Heterochromatin that is arranged in a carthwheel pattern.

definition.value: Any serous secreting cell that is part of the tracheobronchial epithelium.
Any chondrocyte that is part of the tracheobronchial tree.
Any goblet cell that is part of the tracheobronchial epithelium.

value.value: An eosinophil with a ring-shaped nucleus that is resident in the lung parenchyma. In mouse, lung parenchyma resident eosinophils are IL-5-independent Siglec-F(intermediate) CD62L+ CD101(low). In human, they are Siglec-8+ CD62L+ IL-3R(low).
A smooth muscle cell that is part of any lymphatic vessel.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of any blood vessel.
A smooth muscle cell that is part of the tracheobronchial tree.

An epithelial cell of the extrahepatic bile ducts, including the left and right hepatic duct, common hepatic duct, and common bile duct. They are columnar in shape, and have a large nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio relative to small/intrahepatic cholangiocytes.

label.value: endothelial cell of periportal hepatic sinusoid

value.value: An endothelial cell found in the periportal region hepatic sinusoid, near the portal triad. The fenestrae of these cells are larger but fewer in number compared with those of endothelial cells near the centrilobular region of the hepatic sinusoid.

label.value: endothelial cell of pericentral hepatic sinusoid

value.value: An endothelial cell found in the centrilobular region hepatic sinusoid, near the central vein. The fenestrae of these cells are smaller but more numerous compared with those of endothelial cells near the periportal region of the hepatic sinusoid.
Any hepatocyte that is part of the liver lobule periportal region. These cells are primarily involved in oxidative energy metabolism.
Any hepatocyte that is part of the liver lobule midzonal region. These cells have mixed functionality in comparison with those in the other two regions of the liver lobule.
Any hepatocyte that is part of the liver lobule centrilobular region. These cells are the primary location for the biotransformation of drugs.
